        "comment": {
            "name": "comment",
            "type": "com.atlassian.jira.issue.fields.CommentSystemField",
            "value": [
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/12633",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "I do not agree...\n\nThe standard useage of getDate is to use the standard format for dates because the user does not know about formating rules.\n\nBut the standardformat does not always include month and daynames.\nAlso fixing this to the EXACT format you will have the problem that dates are not recognised anymore.\n\n'10.10.2006' and '10.Oktober.2006' and '10.Okt.2006' \n\nare german dates and should all be recognised by the standard format.\nSame useage for all other locales.\n\nOtherwise a user has to seperate if he uses a month name or an abbreviated name or a number.\n\nIn my opinion the standard format should accept all various combinations of dates for a locale and not only one of them.\n\nOtherwise this would be no benefit for the user.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-02-09T01:48:05.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-02-09T01:48:05.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/12680",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=gavin",
                        "name": "gavin",
                        "displayName": "Gavin",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Ok, you convinced me :)\n\nInstead, why not always translate day and month names, if the $format contains 'd' or 'M' or 'EEEE' or 'MMMM'?\nThis feature seems quite useful, and a major advantage unique to the ZF and the i18n components.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=gavin",
                        "name": "gavin",
                        "displayName": "Gavin",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-02-11T18:36:36.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-02-11T18:36:36.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/12682",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "This is already be done by _parseDate()...\n\nEEEE, the full dayname is deleted because having 'Monday' is not enough to say which day was meant.\n\nd, the daynumber, is used as expected\n\nMMMM, the full monthname is parsed if the format defines a full monthname, otherwise the abbreviated monthname is searched and if found converted to a monthnumber.\n\nSo after all actions we have a monthnumber 'M' which is used for parsing through the date.\n\nThe only thing which is now handled else is that if full month is defined also only full months are searched and not the abbreviated ones... but this was only done for speed...\n\nWe can also say that if 'M' is presented within the format always full and abbreviated months have to be searched.\n\nNote:\nThe standardformats from CLDR only define M and MMMM...\nThe formats MM, MMM and MMMMM are not included in this definitions so I did not integrate them for parsing... reason was also speed...",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-02-12T01:17:56.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-02-12T01:17:56.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/12915",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Solved with SVN 3595.\n\nNow full and abbreviated month names are always parsed as soon as a \"M\" is given in the format.\n\nAlso daynames are always parsed as soon as \"E\" is given.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-02-23T15:33:43.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-02-23T15:33:43.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/12917",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=gavin",
                        "name": "gavin",
                        "displayName": "Gavin",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Excellent.  Now we have consistency.  The sequence of processing is also critical to avoid potential bugs.\nFor example, processing abbreviations first might result in wrong matches in some locales\/languages.\n\nI realize that many of the CLDR format specifiers are not supported, but _parseDate() now recognizing all the most popular and frequently occuring specifiers, so I think we are done for now :)",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=gavin",
                        "name": "gavin",
                        "displayName": "Gavin",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-02-23T16:25:00.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-02-23T16:25:00.000+0000"
                }
            ]
        }
    },
